<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-696-297  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 696 297.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Dec 18 1990 v4 n42 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Silicon Beach ships Personal Press. (Silicon Beach Softwareintroduces low-end page layout program) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Silicon Beach Software Inc introduces Personal Press, a newlow-end desktop publishing package aimed at owners of the low-costMacintoshes.andP;  The $299 program uses interactive 'proxies' toprovide graphical previews of such operations as importing textand graphics, scaling fonts and aligning objects.andP;  Users canassemble text and graphics into any of 32 predesigned templateswith an 'AutoCreate' feature.andP;  Advanced features of Personal Pressinclude modules for scanning from within the program, full textand graphics rotation, halftoning and gray-scale image editing.andO;It can import and display 24-bit color graphics files, but canprint only spot color.andP;  Personal Press suffered from many bugs inits early beta versions, according to testers.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Silicon Beach Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Personal Press (Desktop publishing software) (Productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDesktop PublishingLow CostSoftware PackagesLayout.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Layout application aimed at entry levelandM;By Carolyn SaidandM;San Diego -- Silicon Beach Software last week shipped Personal Press, anentry-level page-layout program the company hopes will dovetail with the newlow-cost Macs.andM;&quot;Friendliness is its strong point,&quot; said Doug Miles, a font developer inEllensburg, Wash., and a beta tester of the $299 program.andP;  &quot;[Silicon Beach]put a lot of effort into making it easy to use for non-technical people.&quot;andM;Interactive &quot;proxies&quot; offer graphic previews of such operations as importingtext and graphics, aligning objects, and scaling.andM;An AutoCreate feature lets users assemble text and graphics into one of the32 predesigned templates or a user-generated template.andM;Beta-user Dave Burbank, a design layout consultant in Ithaca, N.Y., said heparticularly likes the Posted Notes feature, which lets users attach commentsto a document.andP;  On the down side, Burbank said, the text tool is availableonly at 100 percent view, and rulers for standard-sized pages don't fit on a9-inch Mac screen, necessitating dragging to access some features.andP;  Milessaid he found the style sheets not comprehensive enough, covering only font,size and style.andM;Despite its &quot;entry-level&quot; positioning, Personal Press offers some advancedfeatures, including modules that allow scanning from within the program,gray-scale image editing, full rotation of textand graphics, and advancedhalftoning.andP;  The program also offers 24-bit color graphic import anddisplaybut prints only spot color.andM;Announced more than a year ago and originally scheduled for release in thefirst quarter of this year, Personal Press has traveled down a rocky road torelease, beta testers said.andP;  &quot;The beta versions have been unusable forday-to-day productivity until a month ago,&quot; Miles said.andM;Silicon Beach and its parent company, Seattle-based Aldus Corp., are workingon file compatibility between Personal Press and Aldus PageMaker.andP;  PersonalPress users currently can import stories from PageMaker; additionalcompatibility will not be available for at least two to three months, SiliconBeach said.andP;  The companies do not offer an upgrade path from Personal Pressto PageMaker.andM;Silicon Beach Software is at 9770 Carroll Center Road, Suite J, San Diego,Calif.andP;  92126.andP;  Phone (619) 695-6956; fax (619) 695-7902.andO;</TEXT></DOC>